  "doc_id": "6710",
  "text": "According to the definition, a TSS is a minimum set of constraints K such that there is at least one variable for which two different minimal solving sets can be found. A minimal solving set leading to a variable v corresponds to a value propagation [CITATION_1] starting usually, but not necessarily, by terminal constraints and leading to v. Therefore, a TSS can also be seen as two distinct value propagations leading to a given variable. This point of view has been adopted as a theoretical tool to develop proofs.",
  "correct_citation": {
